#: ../../../command/list.rst:2
msgid "list"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:4
msgid "Operations on :ref:`semicolon-separated lists <CMake Language Lists>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:7
msgid "Synopsis"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:11
msgid ""
"`Reading`_\n"
"  list(`LENGTH`_ <list> <out-var>)\n"
"  list(`GET`_ <list> <element index> [<index> ...] <out-var>)\n"
"  list(`JOIN`_ <list> <glue> <out-var>)\n"
"  list(`SUBLIST`_ <list> <begin> <length> <out-var>)\n"
"\n"
"`Search`_\n"
"  list(`FIND`_ <list> <value> <out-var>)\n"
"\n"
"`Modification`_\n"
"  list(`APPEND`_ <list> [<element>...])\n"
"  list(`FILTER`_ <list> <INCLUDE|EXCLUDE> <MODE>)\n"
"  list(`INSERT`_ <list> <index> [<element>...])\n"
"  list(`POP_BACK`_ <list> [<out-var>...])\n"
"  list(`POP_FRONT`_ <list> [<out-var>...])\n"
"  list(`PREPEND`_ <list> [<element>...])\n"
"  list(`REMOVE_ITEM`_ <list> <value>...)\n"
"  list(`REMOVE_AT`_ <list> <index>...)\n"
"  list(`REMOVE_DUPLICATES`_ <list>)\n"
"  list(`TRANSFORM`_ <list> <ACTION> [...])\n"
"\n"
"`Ordering`_\n"
"  list(`REVERSE`_ <list>)\n"
"  list(`SORT`_ <list> [...])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:37
msgid "Introduction"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:39
msgid ""
"The list subcommands :cref:`APPEND`, :cref:`INSERT`, :cref:`FILTER`, :cref:"
"`PREPEND`, :cref:`POP_BACK`, :cref:`POP_FRONT`, :cref:`REMOVE_AT`, :cref:"
"`REMOVE_ITEM`, :cref:`REMOVE_DUPLICATES`, :cref:`REVERSE` and :cref:`SORT` "
"may create new values for the list within the current CMake variable scope.  "
"Similar to the :command:`set` command, the ``list`` command creates new "
"variable values in the current scope, even if the list itself is actually "
"defined in a parent scope.  To propagate the results of these operations "
"upwards, use :command:`set` with ``PARENT_SCOPE``, :command:`set` with "
"``CACHE INTERNAL``, or some other means of value propagation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:52
msgid ""
"A list in cmake is a ``;`` separated group of strings.  To create a list, "
"the :command:`set` command can be used.  For example, ``set(var a b c d e)`` "
"creates a list with ``a;b;c;d;e``, and ``set(var \"a b c d e\")`` creates a "
"string or a list with one item in it. (Note that macro arguments are not "
"variables, and therefore cannot be used in ``LIST`` commands.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:59
msgid ""
"Individual elements may not contain an unequal number of ``[`` and ``]`` "
"characters, and may not end in a backslash (``\\``). See :ref:`semicolon-"
"separated lists <CMake Language Lists>` for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:65
msgid ""
"When specifying index values, if ``<element index>`` is 0 or greater, it is "
"indexed from the beginning of the list, with 0 representing the first list "
"element.  If ``<element index>`` is -1 or lesser, it is indexed from the end "
"of the list, with -1 representing the last list element. Be careful when "
"counting with negative indices: they do not start from 0.  -0 is equivalent "
"to 0, the first list element."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:73
msgid "Reading"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:78
msgid "Returns the list's length."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:83
msgid "Returns the list of elements specified by indices from the list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:89
msgid ""
"Returns a string joining all list's elements using the glue string. To join "
"multiple strings, which are not part of a list, use :command:`string(JOIN)`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:98
msgid ""
"Returns a sublist of the given list. If ``<length>`` is 0, an empty list "
"will be returned. If ``<length>`` is -1 or the list is smaller than "
"``<begin>+<length>`` then the remaining elements of the list starting at "
"``<begin>`` will be returned."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:104
msgid "Search"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:109
msgid ""
"Returns the index of the element specified in the list or ``-1`` if it "
"wasn't found."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:113
msgid "Modification"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:118
msgid ""
"Appends elements to the list. If no variable named ``<list>`` exists in the "
"current scope its value is treated as empty and the elements are appended to "
"that empty list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:127
msgid "Includes or removes items from the list that match the mode's pattern."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:129
msgid "``<MODE>`` must be one of the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:131 ../../../command/list.rst:350
msgid "``REGEX``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:132
msgid "Items will be matched against the given regular expression."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:134
msgid "list(FILTER <list> <INCLUDE|EXCLUDE> REGEX <regular_expression>)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:138
msgid ""
"For more information on regular expressions look under :ref:`string(REGEX) "
"<Regex Specification>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:141 ../../../command/list.rst:358
msgid "``PREDICATE``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:142
msgid "Specify a user-defined :command:`function` as a predicate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:144
msgid "list(FILTER <list> <INCLUDE|EXCLUDE> PREDICATE <function>)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:150
msgid ""
"``<function>`` is a user-defined :command:`function` that acts as a unary "
"predicate.  The function must accept exactly two parameters: the input value "
"and the name of an output variable.  The function must set the output "
"variable to a boolean value in the calling scope. The output variable is "
"interpreted using standard CMake boolean evaluation. If the function does "
"not set the output variable, it is an error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:157 ../../../command/list.rst:318
#: ../../../command/list.rst:375 ../../../command/list.rst:480
msgid "Example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:159
msgid ""
"function(file_exists path result)\n"
"  if(EXISTS \"${path}\")\n"
"    set(${result} TRUE PARENT_SCOPE)\n"
"  else()\n"
"    set(${result} FALSE PARENT_SCOPE)\n"
"  endif()\n"
"endfunction()\n"
"\n"
"set(candidate_files main.c missing.c utils.c)\n"
"list(FILTER candidate_files INCLUDE PREDICATE file_exists)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:175
msgid ""
"Inserts elements to the list to the specified index. It is an error to "
"specify an out-of-range index. Valid indexes are *0* to *N* where *N* is the "
"length of the list, inclusive. An empty list has length 0. If no variable "
"named ``<list>`` exists in the current scope its value is treated as empty "
"and the elements are inserted in that empty list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:187
msgid ""
"If no variable name is given, removes exactly one element. Otherwise, with "
"*N* variable names provided, assign the last *N* elements' values to the "
"given variables and then remove the last *N* values from ``<list>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:197
msgid ""
"If no variable name is given, removes exactly one element. Otherwise, with "
"*N* variable names provided, assign the first *N* elements' values to the "
"given variables and then remove the first *N* values from ``<list>``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:207
msgid ""
"Insert elements to the 0th position in the list. If no variable named "
"``<list>`` exists in the current scope its value is treated as empty and the "
"elements are prepended to that empty list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:214
msgid "Removes all instances of the given items from the list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:219
msgid "Removes items at given indices from the list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:224
msgid ""
"Removes duplicated items in the list. The relative order of items is "
"preserved, but if duplicates are encountered, only the first instance is "
"preserved."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:234
msgid ""
"Transforms the list by applying an ``<ACTION>`` to all or, by specifying a "
"``<SELECTOR>``, to the selected elements of the list, storing the result in-"
"place or in the specified output variable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:240
msgid ""
"The ``TRANSFORM`` sub-command does not change the number of elements in the "
"list. If a ``<SELECTOR>`` is specified, only some elements will be changed, "
"the other ones will remain the same as before the transformation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:244
msgid ""
"``<ACTION>`` specifies the action to apply to the elements of the list. "
"``<ACTION>`` must be one of the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:247
msgid ""
":command:`APPEND <string(APPEND)>`, :command:`PREPEND <string(PREPEND)>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:248
msgid "Append, prepend specified value to each element of the list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:254
msgid ""
":command:`TOLOWER <string(TOLOWER)>`, :command:`TOUPPER <string(TOUPPER)>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:255
msgid "Convert each element of the list to lower, upper characters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:261
msgid ":command:`STRIP <string(STRIP)>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:262
msgid "Remove leading and trailing spaces from each element of the list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:268
msgid ":command:`GENEX_STRIP <string(GENEX_STRIP)>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:269
msgid ""
"Strip any :manual:`generator expressions <cmake-generator-expressions(7)>` "
"from each element of the list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:277
msgid ":command:`REPLACE <string(REGEX REPLACE)>`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:278
msgid ""
"Match the regular expression as many times as possible and substitute the "
"replacement expression for the match for each element of the list (same "
"semantic as :command:`string(REGEX REPLACE)`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:287
msgid ""
"The ``^`` anchor now matches only at the beginning of the input element "
"instead of the beginning of each repeated search. See policy :policy:"
"`CMP0186`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:292
msgid "``APPLY``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:293
msgid ""
"Invoke a user-defined :command:`function` for each element of the list. The "
"function must accept exactly two parameters: the input value and the name of "
"an output variable.  The function must set the output variable in the "
"calling scope."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:304
msgid ""
"``<function>`` is a :command:`function` with exactly two formal parameters. "
"Set the output variable via :command:`set(\\<variable\\> \\<value\\> "
"PARENT_SCOPE) <set>`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:308
msgid ""
"function(<function> <input> <output>)\n"
"  # Transform <input>, store result in ${<output>}\n"
"  set(${<output>} \"<result>\" PARENT_SCOPE)\n"
"endfunction()"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:315
msgid ""
"Before each invocation, the output variable is unset in the calling scope to "
"prevent stale values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:320
msgid ""
"function(make_absolute in out)\n"
"  cmake_path(ABSOLUTE_PATH in BASE_DIRECTORY "
"\"${CMAKE_CURRENT_SOURCE_DIR}\")\n"
"  set(${out} \"${in}\" PARENT_SCOPE)\n"
"endfunction()\n"
"\n"
"set(mylist main.c utils.c io.c)\n"
"list(TRANSFORM mylist APPLY make_absolute)\n"
"# mylist is now absolute paths relative to CMAKE_CURRENT_SOURCE_DIR"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:331
msgid ""
"``<SELECTOR>`` determines which elements of the list will be transformed. "
"Only one type of selector can be specified at a time. When given, "
"``<SELECTOR>`` must be one of the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:335
msgid "``AT``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:336
msgid "Specify a list of indexes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:338
msgid "list(TRANSFORM <list> <ACTION> AT <index> [<index> ...] ...)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:342
msgid "``FOR``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:343
msgid ""
"Specify a range with, optionally, an increment used to iterate over the "
"range."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:346
msgid "list(TRANSFORM <list> <ACTION> FOR <start> <stop> [<step>] ...)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:351
msgid ""
"Specify a regular expression. Only elements matching the regular expression "
"will be transformed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:354
msgid "list(TRANSFORM <list> <ACTION> REGEX <regular_expression> ...)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:359
msgid ""
"Specify a user-defined :command:`function` as a predicate. Only elements for "
"which the function returns a true value will be transformed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:363
msgid "list(TRANSFORM <list> <ACTION> PREDICATE <function> ...)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:369
msgid ""
"``<function>`` is a user-defined :command:`function` with exactly two formal "
"parameters: the input value and the name of an output variable.  The "
"function must set the output variable to a boolean value.  Standard CMake "
"boolean evaluation is used. If the function does not set the output "
"variable, it is an error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:377
msgid ""
"function(is_relative path result)\n"
"  if(NOT IS_ABSOLUTE \"${path}\")\n"
"    set(${result} TRUE PARENT_SCOPE)\n"
"  else()\n"
"    set(${result} FALSE PARENT_SCOPE)\n"
"  endif()\n"
"endfunction()\n"
"\n"
"set(search_paths /usr/include src lib /opt/lib)\n"
"list(TRANSFORM search_paths PREPEND \"${CMAKE_CURRENT_SOURCE_DIR}/\"\n"
"     PREDICATE is_relative)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:393
msgid "Ordering"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:398
msgid "Reverses the contents of the list in-place."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:404
msgid "Sorts the list in-place alphabetically."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:406
msgid "Added the ``COMPARE``, ``CASE``, and ``ORDER`` options."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:409
msgid "Added the ``COMPARE NATURAL`` option."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:412
msgid ""
"Use the ``COMPARE`` keyword to select the comparison method for sorting. The "
"``<compare>`` option should be one of:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:415
msgid "``STRING``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:416
msgid ""
"Sorts a list of strings alphabetically. This is the default behavior if the "
"``COMPARE`` option is not given."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:419
msgid "``FILE_BASENAME``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:420
msgid "Sorts a list of pathnames of files by their basenames."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:422
msgid "``NATURAL``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:423
msgid ""
"Sorts a list of strings using natural order (see ``strverscmp(3)`` manual), "
"i.e. such that contiguous digits are compared as whole numbers. For example: "
"the following list *10.0 1.1 2.1 8.0 2.0 3.1* will be sorted as *1.1 2.0 2.1 "
"3.1 8.0 10.0* if the ``NATURAL`` comparison is selected where it will be "
"sorted as *1.1 10.0 2.0 2.1 3.1 8.0* with the ``STRING`` comparison."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:431
msgid ""
"Use the ``CASE`` keyword to select a case sensitive or case insensitive sort "
"mode.  The ``<case>`` option should be one of:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:434
msgid "``SENSITIVE``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:435
msgid ""
"List items are sorted in a case-sensitive manner. This is the default "
"behavior if the ``CASE`` option is not given."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:438
msgid "``INSENSITIVE``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:439
msgid ""
"List items are sorted case insensitively.  The order of items which differ "
"only by upper/lowercase is not specified."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:442
msgid ""
"To control the sort order, the ``ORDER`` keyword can be given. The "
"``<order>`` option should be one of:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:445
msgid "``ASCENDING``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:446
msgid ""
"Sorts the list in ascending order. This is the default behavior when the "
"``ORDER`` option is not given."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:449
msgid "``DESCENDING``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:450
msgid "Sorts the list in descending order."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:452
msgid ""
"Instead of the built-in ``COMPARE`` methods, a user-defined comparison :"
"command:`function` may be used with the ``COMPARATOR`` keyword."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:457
msgid ""
"``COMPARATOR`` is mutually exclusive with ``COMPARE``.  The ``CASE`` and "
"``ORDER`` options may still be used alongside ``COMPARATOR``: the ``CASE`` "
"filter is applied to both values before they are passed to the function, and "
"``ORDER DESCENDING`` reverses the comparison by swapping the two arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:463
msgid ""
"The function must accept exactly three parameters: two input values and the "
"name of an output variable.  It must set the output variable to a boolean "
"value (``TRUE`` if the first value should come before the second, ``FALSE`` "
"otherwise) in the calling scope. If the function does not set the output "
"variable, it is an error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:469
msgid ""
"The comparator must define a `strict weak ordering <https://en.wikipedia.org/"
"wiki/Weak_ordering#Strict_weak_orderings>`_. In particular:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:473
msgid ""
"It must return ``FALSE`` when comparing an element to itself (irreflexivity)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:475
msgid ""
"If it returns ``TRUE`` for ``(a, b)``, it must return ``FALSE`` for ``(b, "
"a)`` (asymmetry)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:478
msgid "An error is raised if the comparator violates these requirements."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../command/list.rst:482
msgid ""
"function(version_less a b result)\n"
"  if(\"${a}\" VERSION_LESS \"${b}\")\n"
"    set(${result} TRUE PARENT_SCOPE)\n"
"  else()\n"
"    set(${result} FALSE PARENT_SCOPE)\n"
"  endif()\n"
"endfunction()\n"
"\n"
"set(versions 3.1 1.2 2.0 1.10)\n"
"list(SORT versions COMPARATOR version_less)\n"
"# versions is now: 1.2;1.10;2.0;3.1"
msgstr ""
